paragraphs: England continue to impress in this series after whitewashing the Windies 3-0 in the ODIs. The Windies need to find a way to get better with both bat and ball otherwise it will be late for them. Join us day after tomorrow for the second T20I from Bristol. We hope you enjoyed our coverage. Until next time, goodbye and cheers!

Harry Brook | England captain: Really pleased to get the win. To have Liam and Rash (Rashid) operating the way they do it was great. Unbelievable, to have him (Buttler) in the team, to have him bat in the top three, it's an honour. It's quite a big field, it's hard to hit boundaries in the middle-order, you have to take twos, as I said to have Liam and Rash bowling in tandem was great. We had a bit of a tricky period with the bat in the middle overs, If we can get a few more boundaries in the middle that would be great, that's one learning and also running hard between the wickets. Also, if we can nail the yorkers at the backend, that would be great.

Shai Hope | West Indies captain: (On what didn't work for them today) Can't really pinpoint one or the other, the bowlers didn't bowl well in the powerplay but they pulled it back towards the end. Every single ground is different, you have to adapt to the conditions, we tried to understand the dimensions, also the pitch was a bit slow. A lot of teams like to throw spin at the West Indies, we have to play better, we have a powerful and destructive batting lineup, we have got two games to go, so need to come back better.

Liam Dawson | Player of the Match: (On his bowling performance and return to the English side) Really good, pleasing to contribute to a really good win. When you got 190 on the board, you can bowl defensively, tried to keep it simple and thankfully it worked. It's been three-and-a-half years since I played, little bit nervous but happy to contribute. They have got extreme power so trying to keep it away from their arc, they are really good players.

22:07 Local Time, 21:07 GMT, 02:37 IST: Brook begins his T20I tenure as captain on a winning note. It was a good toss to win for England and they posted a slightly above-par score on a slowish surface on the back of a terrific 59-ball 96 from Buttler. The Windies needed to begin quickly but it didn't quite happen. They lost Charles and Hope early and had a middling powerplay in terms of scoring as well. Then the English spinners took over and extracted good turn and purchase from the surface to keep the pressure on the visitors intact. There was a brief period where Lewis hit some lusty blows but Bethell had the last laugh as he dismissed the southpaw to peg the visitors back again. Dawson took two wickets in an over soon after and that derailed the visitors. Rashid was tidy in his spell and the match slowly went away from the visitors' reach. They kept losing wickets and the pressure got the better of them as they fell short by 21 runs. Stick around for the presentations...

Potts to Shepherd, out Caught by Will Jacks!! Potts ends with a wicket! A comprehensive victory for England. A slower shortish delivery on off, Shepherd goes for the pull but mistimes it towards deep mid-wicket where Jacks pouches it safely. Shepherd c Will Jacks b Potts 16(12) [4s-2]
Potts to Shepherd, THATS OUT!! Caught!!
Potts to Shepherd, FOUR, low full-toss wide outside off, Shepherd swings hard at it but gets a thick inside edge past his off-stump and beats the keeper to his left to roll away to the fence behind
Potts to Shepherd, wide, very full wide outside off, Shepherd lets it go. Wided again by the umpire, was just beyond the tramline

Potts to Shepherd, 2 runs, a low full-toss wide outside off, Shepherd tries to go over long-off but ends up slicing it over extra cover. Duckett runs to his left and keeps the batters down to a couple
Potts to Holder, 1 run, skiddy hard length delivery outside off, Holder mistimes his flat-batted stroke to long-on
Potts to Holder, wide, slower full ball wide outside off which cuts the tramline, wided again
Potts to Holder, FOUR, hit hard! Fractionally overpitched outside off, Holder lines it up and smashes it past Potts. Long-off has no chance to stop it
Potts to Holder, wide, slower short of length ball wide outside off, Holder tries to cut but misses. Wided
Potts to Shepherd, 1 run, a low full-toss outside off, Shepherd swings hard at it and gets it off the bottom half of the bat to deep mid-wicket

Brydon Carse to Holder, FOUR, fullish ball angling down leg, Holder tries to flick it behind square but ends up getting it off the inner half. Buttler dives to his left but evades him and runs through to the fence
Brydon Carse to Holder, no run, another bouncer outside off, Holder swings at it but misses. Looked pretty high this time but the umpire signals one bouncer for the over
Brydon Carse to Holder, no run, a sharp short delivery on off, Holder tries to pull but misses. Holder looks towards the square leg umpire searching for a wide who stays unmoved

Brydon Carse to Holder, 2 runs, Holder backs away and Brydon Carse follows him with a back of a length delivery. Flat-batted to long-on and some good running between the wickets allows the batters to take a couple
Brydon Carse to Shepherd, 1 run, fuller length ball angling in from outside off, Shepherd heaves it off the inner half to deep mid-wicket
